        "# what problems does pydantic solve\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. data validation, type validation errors are handled.\n",
        "# Example: if i create this function\n",
        "\n",
        "# def insert_db(name,age):\n",
        "#   print(\"name\")\n",
        "#   print(\"age\")\n",
        "#   print(\"inserted in db\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# insert_db('pavan','30')\n",
        "\n",
        "# this writes the name n age to database. but here age is given as str rather than int. one way to prevent this is writing the code as below:\n",
        "\n",
        "# def insert_db(name:str,age:int):\n",
        "#   print(\"name\")\n",
        "#   print(\"age\")\n",
        "#   print(\"inserted in db\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# insert_db('pavan',-30)\n",
        "\n",
        "# in this, we have given the type of the 2 objects as str and int. but still we can pass -ve int as value for age. again no way of validating this error as well. we can also write the logic as this\n",
        "\n",
        "# def insert_db(name,age):\n",
        "\n",
        "#   if type(name) == str and type(age)==int:\n",
        "#     print(\"name\")\n",
        "#     print(\"age\")\n",
        "#     print(\"inserted into DB\")\n",
        "#   else\n",
        "#     raise Typeerror\n",
        "\n",
        "# so if you see, we are writing multiple lines of code to validate the input taken up the function, their type and also the values inputted.\n",
        "\n",
        "# The main problem with python here is the objects are dynamic meaning an object can be assigned values if diff type - str,int, float etc., while in c,c++,java objects are assigned a type during instanciation.\n",
        "\n",
        "# To solve this, we have the concept of pydantic.\n",
        "\n",
        "# What benefits pydantic provides:\n",
        "# 1. it helps in data validation i.e., if you want to accept certain type of input or certain range of values, you dont have to write the code for this logic multiple times. instead you create a pydantic class which handles this.\n",
        "\n",
        "# How does pydantic doe this:\n",
        "# 1. here we follow a 3 step process:\n",
        "# Step 1: create a class in pydantic, indicating the type and values to be accepted. define the ideal schema for that class/model\n",
        "# Step 2: instantiate the model/class with reference values to help it understand the inputs\n",
        "# Step 3: pass the validated model object to all functions"
